cs.ET, cs.AR, cs.EM, cs.CE, cs.NE 

The paper discusses modifying a commercial NOR flash memory array for analog computing applications, which involves tuning individual floating-gate cells with high precision. This suggests that the paper could belong to the sub-category of cs.ET (Emerging Technologies), which deals with new and innovative technologies that have the potential to impact computing. Additionally, the paper mentions implementing a four-quadrant vector-by-matrix multiplier, which involves matrix operations and could be related to the sub-category of cs.AR (Hardware Architecture). The use of floating-gate transistors also suggests a potential connection to the sub-category of cs.EM (Electronics Materials), which deals with the design and fabrication of electronic devices. The precision tuning of individual cells could also be related to the sub-category of cs.CE (Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science), which deals with the use of computational methods in engineering and science applications. Finally, the use of analog computing could be related to the sub-category of cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing), which deals with the design and implementation of neural networks and other biologically-inspired computing systems.
